The black box from the Ethiopian Airlines flight that crashed on Sunday has been recovered by investigators at the crash site, according to an accident bulletin issued by the airline on Monday. “The Digital Flight Data Recorder(DFDR) and Cockpit Voice Recorder(CVR) of ET302 have been recovered,” the statement read. Ethiopian Airlines flight ET 302/10 March in schedule service from Addis Ababa to Nairobi had crashed yesterday shortly after take off., killing the 149 passengers and 8 crew members on board. The aircraft with registration number ET- AVJ is the second Boeing 737-800MAX to crash shortly after take off in months. While investigations are ongoing, Ethiopian announced it had grounded B-737-800MAX fleet of 5 effective Sunday, the day of the crash. The airline had ordered 30 B-737-800MAX aircraft last year, but only five have been delivered. “Although we don’t yet know the cause of the accident, we had to decide to ground the particular fleet as extra safety precaution,” the airline said. Meanwhile, shares of Boeing fell 9 percent in premarket trading on Monday as Ethiopian and some airlines grounded the company’s best selling 737 MAX 8 aircraft.